As many people recommended sorting as a viable approach, here some remarks on sorting. First, yes, it would give you a correct result but there is a price to pay which is speed and well it is just an unnecessarily complex solution.
 
Sorting based on comparisons and without any pre-conditions [cannot be done faster than in `O(n log n)`](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/lower-bound-on-comparison-based-sorting-algorithms/). It is obvious that the solution above needs `O(n)` time thus is a complexity class faster. Also the constants (which are ignored in big-O notation) are quite small in the above solution, so even if some pre-conditions were met and you could use a special sorting algorithm like [Map sort](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proxmap_sort) (or alike) which run in `O(n)` (again: under certain conditions) the above solution would still be faster and, not to mention, much simpler. So don&#39;t make your life harder than it needs to be.

