answers.body_markdown:
Change this: 

    @Repository
    public interface ExpenseRepository extends CrudRepository&lt;Expense, Integer&gt;{
        @Query(&quot;SELECT min(dtDate) as dtDate ,Max(dtDate) as dtDate FROM Expense&quot;)
        Iterable&lt;Expense&gt; getAvlRptDates();
    }

To the following changing Iterable to Optional which returns a list of Jsons:

    @Repository
    public interface ExpenseRepository extends CrudRepository&lt;Expense, Integer&gt;{
        @Query(&quot;SELECT min(dtDate) as dtDate ,Max(dtDate) as dtDate FROM Expense&quot;)
        Optional&lt;Expense&gt; getAvlRptDates();
    }

Now, you will get some sort of JSON but not the kind of json that meets official standards.

So my recommendation is to do:

    @Repository
    public interface ExpenseRepository extends CrudRepository&lt;Expense, Integer&gt;{
        @Query(&quot;SELECT min(dtDate) as dtDate ,Max(dtDate) as dtDate FROM Expense&quot;)
        Expense[] getAvlRptDates();
    }

Where it return a single iterable, then convert the contents of the iterable to json one by one. See below link: 

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/15332733/how-to-convert-list-data-into-json-in-java

Hope it helps.

